00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.975
Well, last time we had seen
that when you write this

00:00:10.975 --> 00:00:14.975
electron configuration,
that that electron

00:00:14.975 --> 00:00:20.926
configuration is a shorthand way
of writing the wave functions

00:00:20.926 --> 00:00:26.097
for the electrons in a
multi-electron atom within this

00:00:26.097 --> 00:00:33.585
one electron wave approximation.
But we also noted that at most

00:00:33.585 --> 00:00:40.159
we gave, or we assigned a
hydrogen-like wave function to

00:00:40.159 --> 00:00:44.940
two electrons.
And we noted that that was

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:51.513
because of something you already
knew about called spin.

00:00:51.513 --> 00:00:57.609
And spin, we saw last time,
was a quantum mechanical

00:00:57.609 --> 00:01:02.952
phenomenon.
Spin is the intrinsic angular

00:01:02.952 --> 00:01:06.312
momentum, built into the
particle.

00:01:06.312 --> 00:01:12.218
And we saw that that spin is
designated by a fourth quantum

00:01:12.218 --> 00:01:16.087
number.
That fourth quantum number here

00:01:16.087 --> 00:01:21.178
is m sub s,
and it had two allowed values,

00:01:21.178 --> 00:01:28.000
and those allowed values were
one half and minus one half.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.867
And we said that those two
allowed values or those two

00:01:33.867 --> 00:01:38.739
states represented a spin up and
a spin down.

00:01:38.739 --> 00:01:44.496
Two different polarities,
in a sense, of this quantum

00:01:44.496 --> 00:01:48.150
mechanical phenomenon called
spin.

00:01:48.150 --> 00:01:53.132
How was spin actually
experimentally observed?

00:01:53.132 --> 00:01:59.000
Well, really thanks to these
two gentlemen.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.765
Here is Uhlenbeck and Goudsmit.
These were very young

00:02:03.765 --> 00:02:07.522
scientists.
I think post-docs at the time.

00:02:07.522 --> 00:02:12.929
And what they were doing was
looking at the emission spectra

00:02:12.929 --> 00:02:16.137
from sodium atoms.
And this is 1925,

00:02:16.137 --> 00:02:20.536
and so they knew enough,
already, to know at what

00:02:20.536 --> 00:02:25.026
frequency they should expect to
see some emission.

00:02:25.026 --> 00:02:29.425
And so they looked at the
emission, dispersed it,

00:02:29.425 --> 00:02:35.332
looked at that frequency.
And instead of seeing emission

00:02:35.332 --> 00:02:39.064
at that particular frequency
where they expected,

00:02:39.064 --> 00:02:43.495
they saw, so if this is the
expected, what they really saw

00:02:43.495 --> 00:02:47.927
was some emission at a little
bit lower frequency and some

00:02:47.927 --> 00:02:51.115
emission at a little bit higher
frequency.

00:02:51.115 --> 00:02:55.391
Not much but a little bit lower
and a little bit higher.

00:02:55.391 --> 00:02:58.812
And in spectroscopy,
this kind of emission is

00:02:58.812 --> 00:03:04.922
actually called the doublet.
Well, they were quite excited

00:03:04.922 --> 00:03:11.271
about it, and thought much about
the reason why there might be a

00:03:11.271 --> 00:03:14.798
doublet.
And they reasoned that they

00:03:14.798 --> 00:03:20.643
could explain that doublet if
the electron were existing in

00:03:20.643 --> 00:03:24.775
one of two states,
one of two spin states.

00:03:24.775 --> 00:03:30.909
This was revolutionary.
And so they took their results

00:03:30.909 --> 00:03:36.242
excitedly to the resident
established scientist that was

00:03:36.242 --> 00:03:42.060
closest, who was Wolfgang Pauli.
And Wolfgang Pauli was not a

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:47.684
nice man, but they told Wolfgang
Pauli about what they saw.

00:03:47.684 --> 00:03:52.242
And Wolfgang said,
rubbish, you publish that and

00:03:52.242 --> 00:03:56.121
you will destroy your scientific
careers.

00:03:56.121 --> 00:04:00.000
And so they left,
dejectedly.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.450
No sooner had the door shut,
than Wolfgang sat down and

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:09.065
wrote a paper on the presence of
a fourth quantum number,

00:04:09.065 --> 00:04:12.280
m sub s.
One of the travesties,

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:15.000
really, in the history of
science.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.791
That is well known now.
But it really did take,

00:04:18.791 --> 00:04:22.087
though, Dirac,
another three years later,

00:04:22.087 --> 00:04:25.796
to actually show where this m
sub s came from,

00:04:25.796 --> 00:04:30.000
this fourth quantum number came
from.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.870
He had to use the relativistic
SchrÃ¶dinger equation,

